Boolean Casting
 The $boolean() function casts an argument to a Boolean using specific rules:
 - true remains unchanged.
 - An empty string ("") evaluates to false.
  - A non-empty string evaluates to true.
 - Numeric 0 evaluates to false, and any non-zero number evaluates to true.
 - An array evaluates to true if it contains at least one truthy value. 
 - An empty array evaluates to false. 
 - An object evaluates to true if it is non-empty. 
 - A function evaluates to false

name:
$keys():
 - Signature: $keys(object)
 - Returns an array containing the keys in the object.
 - If the argument is an array of objects, the returned array
 contains a de-duplicated list of all the keys in all the objects.

$lookup():
 - Signature: $lookup(object, key)
 - Returns the value associated with the specified key in the object.
 - If the first argument is an array of objects,
 it searches all objects and returns values associated with occurrences of the key.

$spread():
 - Signature: $spread(object)
 - Splits an object containing key/value pairs into an array of objects,
 each with a single key/value pair from the input object.
 - If the parameter is an array of objects, the resultant array contains
 an object for every key/value pair in every object in the supplied array.

$merge():
 - Signature: $merge(array<object>)
 - Merges an array of objects into a single object containing
 all key/value pairs from each object in the input array.
 - If any input objects contain the same key, the returned object
 will contain the value of the last occurrence in the array.
